There are a few truly exceptional individuals for this job, individuals who have demonstrated their skills in economic development, intelligence, personal integrity, and political and organizational skills. These potential candidates include former Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, a Yale graduate who is now teaching at the university and has been heavily praised in a recent editorial in the Financial Times. Other candidates include Arminio Fraga, a Princeton graduate and former head of Brazil’s central bank, and Kemal Dervis, a former Vice President of the World Bank who taught at Princeton and successfully helped Turkey out of a crisis. Why should the world settle for less than candidates of this calibre?
